## bpfsentry — auditd rules for the bpf() syscall.
##
## bpfsentry SHIPS these rules but never loads them into the kernel. Install them
## yourself after review (see deploy/README.md). On a workstation that should NOT
## be running eBPF at all, every bpf() call is worth recording; on a host that
## does run Cilium/Tetragon, correlate the key against the legitimate-loader PIDs
## (the same allowlist the Tetragon policy uses) before escalating.
##
## Layer 2 (load-time visibility), auditd variant. This is the cheapest tripwire:
## it needs no eBPF of its own and so cannot be hidden by a sys_bpf hook the way an
## on-box eBPF EDR can.

## --- the bpf() syscall on both ABIs ---
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S bpf -k bpf_activity
-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S bpf -k bpf_activity

## --- bpffs pin directory: a program pinned here persists across the loader exiting ---
-w /sys/fs/bpf -p wa -k bpf_pin

## --- bpftool itself (legit enumeration vs. an attacker probing the BPF subsystem) ---
-w /usr/sbin/bpftool -p x -k bpf_tool
-w /usr/bin/bpftool -p x -k bpf_tool
